UPPER BOUND IN A SORTED ARRAY

You are given a sorted array nums of size n. Your task is to find the upper bound of an integer x.

The upper bound of x is defined as the smallest index i such that nums[i] is greater than x.

If no such index exists, return n (the size of the array).

FUNCTION DESCRIPTION

Function name: upperBound

This function finds the upper bound index of a given value in a sorted array.

PARAMETERS

nums
A sorted array of integers

x
The target integer

RETURN VALUE

Return the smallest index i such that nums[i] > x
Return n if no such index exists

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ n ≤ 100000
-100000 < nums[i], x < 100000
nums is sorted in ascending order

INPUT FORMAT

First line contains an integer n
Second line contains n space-separated integers representing the array
Third line contains an integer x

OUTPUT FORMAT

Print a single integer — the upper bound index

SAMPLE INPUT

6
1 3 5 7 9 11
6

SAMPLE OUTPUT

3

EXPLANATION

The first element greater than 6 is 7 at index 3

SAMPLE INPUT

5
2 4 4 4 6
4

SAMPLE OUTPUT

4

EXPLANATION

The first element greater than 4 is 6 at index 4

 static int upperBound(int[] nums, int x) {
        int left=0;
        int right=nums.length-1;
        int a=nums.length;
        while(left<=right)
        {
            int mid=(left+right)/2;
            if(nums[mid]>x)
            {
                a=mid;
                right=mid-1;
            }
            else{
                left=mid+1;
            }
        } return a;
    }
